<article>
    <h1>HDMI 2.1 stan&#xAD;dard not widely adopted yet</h1>
    <h2></h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20200902/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-09-02"><time>2020-09-02</time></a>
        - <span>LIFE | TECH</span>
        - <span role="byline">vin&#xAD;chang@sph.com.sg</span>
    </section>

    <p>But while HDMI 2.1 of­fers plenty of ben­e­fits to gamers, the TV in­dus­try is not mak­ing it easy for gamers be­cause man­u­fac­tur­ers can la­bel their TVs as HDMI 2.1-com­pat­i­ble with­out im­ple­ment­ing all of the stan­dard’s fea­tures.</p>
    <p>For in­stance, Sony’s Z8H, which is la­belled as ready for the PS5, does not sup­port VRR, though it sup­ports other PS5 fea­tures, such as 8K and 4K res­o­lu­tion at 120Hz.</p>
    <p>An­other is­sue for gamers look­ing to buy a new TV is the ac­tual avail­abil­ity of TVs with HDMI 2.1 ports. While the first TVs with HDMI 2.1 sup­port came out last year, the stan­dard has yet to be adopted by all TV mak­ers.</p>
    <p>Mr Loo Wee Teck, head of con­sumer elec­tron­ics at mar­ket re­search firm Euromon­i­tor In­ter­na­tional, says HDMI 2.1 will likely be found only in newer high-end TVs, such as Oled mod­els.</p>
    <p>“Due to the price sensitivit­y of con­sumers in this cur­rent cli­mate, most of the LCD TVs launched will not sup­port HDMI 2.1,” he says.</p>
    <p>Philips, for in­stance, will not have HDMI 2.1 sup­port in its TVs this year while Pana­sonic is adding ALLM only to some of its mod­els.</p>
    <p>Mean­while, LG and Sam­sung ap­pear to be the best choices as most of their mid- and higher-range TVs have all the key gam­ing fea­tures (4K at 120Hz, VRR and ALLM).</p>


</article>

